  "doc_id": "6849",
  "text": "Fractional photothermolysis (FPT; Fraxel SR laser) using the 1,550-nm nonablative wavelength has a variety of clinical applications, including pigmented lesions, periorbital rhytides, skin resurfacing, melasma, actinic keratosis, and surgical scars [CITATION_1] . Microscopic laser columns penetrate deep into sub layers of skin to create multiple evenly-spaced microthermal zones of injury. Within these damaged areas, localized epidermal necrosis and collagen denaturation occur, followed by an expulsion of epidermal debris and neocollagenesis, while the nonablative areas serve as the epithelial bridge to expedite the remodeling process with tighter, fresher, and more youthful-looking skin [CITATION_2] .",
